<TITLE> European shares at day's lows on Merrill downgrade </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares hit session lows on Wednesday, tracking a fall in US stocks after a downgrade to US investment bank Merrill Lynch's credit rating following the company's first quarterly loss in six years. Standard & Poor's cut its rating on Merrill Lynch, the world's largest brokerage, prompting a fall in US bank stocks that triggered a 0.6-percent slide in the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares to 1,549.11 points, just off the day's low at 1,546.32. Banks were the largest negative weight on the FTSEurofirst. Merrill earlier reported a $2.3-billion net loss for the third quarter, its first quarterly loss in six years. "Banks are still a big worry and the results from Merrill have hit the sector further," one trader said. U.S. benchmark stock indexes were down between 1.5 and 2.7 percent, while short-dated U.S. Treasury yields fell to their lowest level in two years as prices for government debt rallied. Across European stock markets, London's FTSE 100 index staged a sharp reversal, falling 0.8 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX shed 0.3 percent and Paris' CAC 40 fell 0.9 perce
